qx|N3,|cs|1|ht|b|fp|1|cp|4|at|^-{  Introduction to The Weak 1NT Opener - Part 1 of 3   }
|FP||va|4|AT|{  by Howard Schutzman - 4 Way Transfers with Pre-Accepts  }
^-|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|You can play the weak NT with whatever transfer methods you prefer. This includes simply playing major suit transfers, or playing 2@S as forcing 3@C from opener, which you will either pass or correct to 3@D. However, 4 way transfers with pre-accepts work particularly well with the weak NT. Let me first explain the mechanics (assume your partner opens 1NT): |
PG| ***** 47 ***** |


AT|

If you bid 2@D or 2@H, these are normal major suit transfers, guaranteeing at least 5 cards in the major being transferred to.|
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


AT| 

If you bid 2@S, this is a club transfer guaranteeing 5+ clubs. Opener can either accept or reject the transfer. Over 2@S, opener bids 3@C if he "likes" clubs (has one of the top 3 honors). Otherwise he bids 2NT which denies a top club honor.|
PG| ***** 49 ***** |


AT|

If you bid 2N, this is a diamond transfer, and works similarly to the 2@S bid. Opener can either accept or reject the transfer. Over 2N, opener bids 3@D if he "likes" diamonds (has one of the top 3 honors). Otherwise he bids 3@C which denies a top diamond honor. Note that you must trust your partner to remember that you are playing 4 way transfers, because if partner forgets that 2N is a diamond transfer and considers it invitational instead, he will pass or bid 3N, either of which is likely to be very wrong.|
PG| ***** 50 ***** |


AT| 

With a hand suitable to invite to 3N (e.g. what would be a 2N bid had you not been playing 4 way transfers), first bid 2@C (presumably Stayman at that point) and then bid 2N over partner's response. Note that the 2N bid must be alerted as your invitational sequence that does not guarantee a 4 card major. Additionally, if partner responds 2@H, if you have 4 spades you should rebid 2@S rather than 2N. Therefore a rebid of 2N over a 2@H response denies a 4-card major.|
PG| ***** 51 ***** |


AT| 

Now let me discuss some specifics regarding major suit transfers: |
PG| ***** 52 ***** |


NT||
%%%
cs|1|ht|b|fp|1|cp|4|at|^-{  Introduction to The Weak 1NT Opener - Part 1 of 3   }
|FP||va|4|AT|{  by Howard Schutzman - 4 Way Transfers with Pre-Accepts  }
^-|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|You should transfer if you hold any 5 card major, regardless of hand strength. The only exception is that if you are 5-5 in the majors with less than an invitational hand, you can use Crawling Stayman. You bid 2@H over partner's 2@D response, asking partner to pass or bid 2@S with better spades. I recommend you only use major suit garbage Stayman with 5-9 points or 5-5 in the majors; simply transfer to your 5 card major with 0-4 points, as that is likely to play better. |
PG| ***** 53 ***** |


AT|
 
If you hold an invitational hand (10-11 HCP), you should bid 3 of the major with a six card suit and 2N with a 5 card suit. If you hold a game forcing hand, you should bid 4 of the major with a six card suit (assuming you choose not to play transfers at the 4 level), or 3N with a five card suit. This is the same structure as you play over strong NT, with the point counts adjusted appropriately. |
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


AT|
 
There is some question as to whether partner should “super accept”. If you are conservative by nature, you should play partner must always accept the transfer at the 2 level, in case you have a really bad hand. However, I prefer playing that partner should “super accept” to the 3 level with 4 card support; that has the advantage of getting you to some thin games, and also preempting the opponents even if you have a bad hand. |
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


AT|

Next are some specifics regarding the minor suit transfers: |
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


AT|
 
With less than an invitational hand, the question is whether to play in 1N or 3 of the minor. My recommendation is as follows. |
PG| ***** 57 ***** |


AT|

With a 6 card minor and either shortness (singleton or void) or 6 HCP or less, transfer to the minor. With a 5 card suit, 5-9 HCP, and shortness (singleton or void), transfer to the minor. Otherwise, pass 1N. |
PG| ***** 58 ***** |


AT|
 
With game going points, simply bid 3N even with 5+ cards in the minor.|
PG| ***** 59 ***** |


AT| 

With a 6-card minor suit with 2 of the top 3 honors transfer and bid game if partner accepts the transfer. Otherwise stop in 3 of the minor. Next are some example hands: |
PG| ***** 60 ***** |


NT||

%%example 14
st||pn|You,,Partner,|md|3SAQ876 H98 DAQ98 C98,,,|sv|o|rh||ah|Weak 1NT Opener Example 14|ah|Howard Schutzman|mb|1np|lb|*bPlease make a bid with this hand.^^2h|mb|2h|NT|^B@2
Bid 2@H and bid 3N over partner's 2@S response. You are showing game going points and a 5 card suit.
|hc|saqdaq|
PG| ***** 62 ***** |


lc|haqda|NT||
%%example 15
st||pn|You,,Partner,|md|3S98 HAQ876 DA876 C98,,,|sv|o|rh||ah|Weak 1NT Opener Example 15|ah|Howard Schutzman|mb|1np|lb|*bPlease make a bid with this hand.^^2d|mb|2d|NT|^B@2
Bid 2@D. Bid 2N over partner's 2@H response, showing invitational points and a 5 card suit. If partner bids 3@H over 2N, bid 4@H. If partner bids 3@H over 2@D (assuming you play super accepts), bid 4@H.
|hc|haqda|
PG| ***** 64 ***** |


lc|haqda|NT|| 
%%example 16
st||pn|You,,Partner,|md|3S98 HAQ7654 DK98 C98,,,|sv|o|rh||ah|Weak 1NT Opener Example 16|ah|Howard Schutzman|mb|1np|lb|*bPlease make a bid with this hand.^^2d|mb|2d|NT|^B@2
Bid 2@D. Bid 3@H (invitational) over 2@H.
|hc|haqdk|
PG| ***** 66 ***** |


lc|haqdk|NT||
%%example 17
st||pn|You,,Partner,|md|3SAQ7654 H98 DA876 CT ,,,|sv|o|rh||ah|Weak 1NT Opener Example 17|ah|Howard Schutzman|mb|1np|lb|*bPlease make a bid with this hand.^^2h|mb|2h|NT|^B@2
You bid 2@H. Your bid is 4@H (transfer to 4@S) if you decide to play Texas transfer and partner bid 4@S. Personally, I don't play Texas with most of my weak NT partners. There is no reason to, because opener is no longer the "strong hand". So, not playing Texas, I simply bid 4@S over 1NT. You have a rule of 20 opener (10 HCP + 10 cards in your 2 longest suits = 20), so you should bid game.|hc|saqda|
PG| ***** 68 ***** |


lc|saqda|NT|| 
%%example 18
st||pn|You,,Partner,|md|3SA876 HQ765 D98 C984,,,|sv|o|rh||ah|Weak 1NT Opener Example 18|ah|Howard Schutzman|mb|1np|lb|*bPlease make a bid with this hand.^^2c|mb|2c|NT|^B@2
You could either pass or bid 2@C Crawling Stayman. There are a couple of advantages to Crawling Stayman. If you have a 4-4 major suit fit, you will end up in the same contract as pairs not playing the weak NT. This can be particularly important in match points. And bidding Stayman makes it less likely the opponents will compete.
|hc|sahq|
PG| ***** 70 ***** |


